Join us 11/25 @loveshopauto for the launch of a special apparel capsule, JOK.

JOK, which stands for “Jalopies, Oldtimers, and Kyusha,” is a fictitious car club created by TRUE alumni Dario Smith @bellwether_dario. The collection is inspired by Dario’s grandfather, Bob “CBJ” Mills, who was an organizer for the Brotherhood of Street Racers’s Oakland chapter in the 1970’s. Like the mission of the Brotherhood of Street Racers, JOK is an all inclusive club that brings together people of different backgrounds through the love of cars and thrill of driving. 

We’ll be hosting a midday Party and Car Meet with sounds by another TRUE alumni @dj_juanny. Coffee and other refreshments will be provided by @mimoscoffee.co

Please arrive early to the event as parking will fill up fast. Refer to the third slide for parking details and general rules.

Additionally, the entire J.O.K. collection will be available for purchase at the event, at both @true_sf and @true_oakland, and online at truclothing.net on 11/25.

Jalopies: a slang term dating back to the 1930s meaning “old car.” My grandfather, Bob Mills, knows a lot about Jalopies. His foray into cars and automotive sports started in 1969 when he bought his ’69 Ford Cobra Jet - a car that would earn him the nickname “Cobra Jet Bob” amongst local drag racers. As an organizer for the Brotherhood of Street Racers’s Oakland chapter in the 1970s, he and his crew were integral to the Bay Area’s rich, multicultural car scene. I’m honored to continue our family’s legacy in automotive sports and organize space for local car enthusiasts to commune like my grandfather. 
- @bluetwin_dario 
 
Taking inspiration from CJB’s journey, we’ve developed a jacket symbolic of his original club jacket (seen in slides). “Losing Our Way For a Quarter Century.” We might not always know the destination but for the last 27 years, we’ve been on this trail bringing you a TRUE bay experience.
